Additionally it checks if a given integer x is a multiple of another integer div.  If either condition is not satisfied, the function returns false. This operation ensures that x adheres to specific numeric constraints related to both value and divisibility.\n\n    input:\n        The function takes four integers x, low, high and div. x is the number to be checked, and low and high are the lower and upper bounds of the range, respectively. The function also takes an integer div which is the number to be checked for divisibility.\n\n    output:\n        One output will be given which returns true if both conditions are met, i.e., if x is within the range [low, high] and simultaneously a multiple of div.\n*/\nvoid checkConstraints(int x, int low, int high, int div, int *out)\n{\n    *out = (x >= low && x <= high && x % div == 0);\n}\n```\n\nYou must adhere to the following rules:\n * Do not add an explanation to the code\n * Only give the output function, do not repeat the specification\n * Do not make use of any type of loops. That is, no for, while, do-while or recursive loops\n\nYou are given the following problem description. You must return the code in the following format:\n```C\n/*\n    Nikolay has a lemons, b apples and c pears. He decided to cook a compote. According to the recipe the fruits should be in the ratio 1: 2: 4 . It means that for each lemon in the compote should be exactly 2 apples and exactly 4 pears. You can't crumble up, break up or cut these fruits into pieces. These fruits \u2014 lemons, apples and pears \u2014 should be put in the compote as whole fruits. Your task is to determine the maximum total number of lemons, apples and pears from which Nikolay can cook the compote. It is possible that Nikolay can't use any fruits, in this case print 0 .\n\n    Input\n    The input contains the positive integer a (1 \u2264 a \u2264 1000) \u2014 the number of lemons Nikolay has. The second line contains the positive integer b (1 \u2264 b \u2264 1000) \u2014 the number of apples Nikolay has. The third line contains the positive integer c (1 \u2264 c \u2264 1000) \u2014 the number of pears Nikolay has.\n\n    Output\n    Output the maximum total number of lemons, apples and pears from which Nikolay can cook the compote.\n*/\n\nvoid calculateMaxFruitsForCompote(int a, int b, int c, int *out);\n```\n\nPlease generate the formally verified C code adhering to the problem description.",

                    "tokens_used": 0,
                    "code": "/*\n    Nikolay has a lemons, b apples and c pears. He decided to cook a compote. According to the recipe the fruits should be in the ratio 1: 2: 4 . It means that for each lemon in the compote should be exactly 2 apples and exactly 4 pears. You can't crumble up, break up or cut these fruits into pieces. These fruits \u2014 lemons, apples and pears \u2014 should be put in the compote as whole fruits. Your task is to determine the maximum total number of lemons, apples and pears from which Nikolay can cook the compote. It is possible that Nikolay can't use any fruits, in this case print 0 .\n\n    Input\n    The input contains the positive integer a (1 \u2264 a \u2264 1000) \u2014 the number of lemons Nikolay has. The second line contains the positive integer b (1 \u2264 b \u2264 1000) \u2014 the number of apples Nikolay has. The third line contains the positive integer c (1 \u2264 c \u2264 1000) \u2014 the number of pears Nikolay has.\n\n    Output\n    Output the maximum total number of lemons, apples and pears from which Nikolay can cook the compote.\n*/\n/*@ predicate isValidSolution(integer a, integer b, integer c, integer out) =\n    \\exists integer a_used, b_used, c_used;\n    0 <= a_used <= a &&\n    0 <= b_used <= b &&\n    0 <= c_used <= c &&\n    4 * a_used == 2 * b_used == c_used &&\n    a_used + b_used + c_used == out;\n*/\n\n/*@ predicate existsLargerSolution(integer a, integer b, integer c, integer out) =\n    \\exists integer a_used, b_used, c_used;\n    0 <= a_used <= a &&\n    0 <= b_used <= b &&\n    0 <= c_used <= c &&\n    4 * a_used == 2 * b_used == c_used &&\n    a_used + b_used + c_used > out;\n*/\n\n/*@\n    requires \\valid(out);\n    requires 1 <= a <= 1000;\n    requires 1 <= b <= 1000;\n    requires 1 <= c <= 1000;\n    assigns *out;\n    ensures isValidSolution(a, b, c, *out);\n    ensures !existsLargerSolution(a, b, c, *out);\n*/\nvoid calculateMaxFruitsForCompote(int a, int b, int c, int *out) {\n    int maxLemons = a;\n    int maxApples = b / 2;\n    int maxPears = c / 4;\n    \n    *out = (maxLemons <= maxApples && maxLemons <= maxPears) ? maxLemons : ((maxApples <= maxLemons && maxApples <= maxPears) ? maxApples : maxPears);\n}\n",

The function also takes an integer div which is the number to be checked for divisibility.\n\n    output:\n        One output will be given which returns true if both conditions are met, i.e., if x is within the range [low, high] and simultaneously a multiple of div.\n*/\nvoid checkConstraints(int x, int low, int high, int div, int *out)\n{\n    *out = (x >= low && x <= high && x % div == 0);\n}\n```\n\nYou must adhere to the following rules:\n * Do not add an explanation to the code\n * Only give the output function, do not repeat the specification\n * Do not make use of any type of loops. According to the recipe the fruits should be in the ratio 1: 2: 4 . It means that for each lemon in the compote should be exactly 2 apples and exactly 4 pears. You can't crumble up, break up or cut these fruits into pieces. These fruits \u2014 lemons, apples and pears \u2014 should be put in the compote as whole fruits. It means that for each lemon in the compote should be exactly 2 apples and exactly 4 pears. You can't crumble up, break up or cut these fruits into pieces. These fruits \u2014 lemons, apples and pears \u2014 should be put in the compote as whole fruits. Your task is to determine the maximum total number of lemons, apples and pears from which Nikolay can cook the compote. It is possible that Nikolay can't use any fruits, in this case print 0 .\n\n    Input\n    The input contains the positive integer a (1 \u2264 a \u2264 1000) \u2014 the number of lemons Nikolay has. The third line contains the positive integer c (1 \u2264 c \u2264 1000) \u2014 the number of pears Nikolay has.\n\n    Output\n    Output the maximum total number of lemons, apples and pears from which Nikolay can cook the compote.\n*/\n/*@ predicate isValidSolution(integer a, integer b, integer c, integer out) =\n    \\exists integer a_used, b_used, c_used;\n    0 <= a_used <= a &&\n    0 <= b_used <= b &&\n    0 <= c_used <= c &&\n    4 * a_used == 2 * b_used == c_used &&\n    a_used + b_used + c_used == out;\n*/\n\n/*@ predicate existsLargerSolution(integer a, integer b, integer c, integer out) =\n    \\exists integer a_used, b_used, c_used;\n    0 <= a_used <= a &&\n    0 <= b_used <= b &&\n    0 <= c_used <= c &&\n    4 * a_used == 2 * b_used == c_used &&\n    a_used + b_used + c_used > out;\n*/\n\n/*@\n    requires \\valid(out);\n    requires 1 <= a <= 1000;\n    requires 1 <= b <= 1000;\n    requires 1 <= c <= 1000;\n    assigns *out;\n    ensures isValidSolution(a, b, c, *out);\n    ensures !existsLargerSolution(a, b, c, *out);\n*/\nvoid calculateMaxFruitsForCompote(int a, int b, int c, int *out) {\n    int minApples = a / 2;\n    int minPears = minApples / 2;\n\n    int maxFruits = min(min(minApples, b), min(minPears, c));\n\n    if (maxFruits > 0)\n    {\n        *out = (maxFruits * 7); // 1 lemon + 2 apples + 4 pears = 7 fruits in total\n    }\n    else\n    {\n        *out = 0;\n    }\n}\n",

The function also takes an integer div which is the number to be checked for divisibility.\n\n    output:\n        One output will be given which returns true if both conditions are met, i.e., if x is within the range [low, high] and simultaneously a multiple of div.\n*/\nvoid checkConstraints(int x, int low, int high, int div, int *out)\n{\n    *out = (x >= low && x <= high && x % div == 0);\n}\n```\n\nYou must adhere to the following rules:\n * Do not add an explanation to the code\n * Only give the output function, do not repeat the specification\n * Do not make use of any type of loops. Additionally it checks if a given integer x is a multiple of another integer div.  If either condition is not satisfied, the function returns false. This operation ensures that x adheres to specific numeric constraints related to both value and divisibility.\n\n    input:\n        The function takes four integers x, low, high and div. x is the number to be checked, and low and high are the lower and upper bounds of the range, respectively. The function also takes an integer div which is the number to be checked for divisibility.\n\n    output:\n        One output will be given which returns true if both conditions are met, i.e., if x is within the range [low, high] and simultaneously a multiple of div.\n*/\nvoid checkConstraints(int x, int low, int high, int div, int *out)\n{\n    *out = (x >= low && x <= high && x % div == 0);\n}\n```\n\nYou must adhere to the following rules:\n * Do not add an explanation to the code\n * Only give the output function, do not repeat the specification\n * Do not make use of any type of loops. You must return the code in the following format:\n```C\n/*\n    Nikolay has a lemons, b apples and c pears. He decided to cook a compote. According to the recipe the fruits should be in the ratio 1: 2: 4 . It means that for each lemon in the compote should be exactly 2 apples and exactly 4 pears. You can't crumble up, break up or cut these fruits into pieces. These fruits \u2014 lemons, apples and pears \u2014 should be put in the compote as whole fruits. Your task is to determine the maximum total number of lemons, apples and pears from which Nikolay can cook the compote. It is possible that Nikolay can't use any fruits, in this case print 0 .\n\n    Input\n    The input contains the positive integer a (1 \u2264 a \u2264 1000) \u2014 the number of lemons Nikolay has. The second line contains the positive integer b (1 \u2264 b \u2264 1000) \u2014 the number of apples Nikolay has. The third line contains the positive integer c (1 \u2264 c \u2264 1000) \u2014 the number of pears Nikolay has.\n\n    Output\n    Output the maximum total number of lemons, apples and pears from which Nikolay can cook the compote.\n*/\n\nvoid calculateMaxFruitsForCompote(int a, int b, int c, int *out);\n```\nThe previous code attempt did not verify: \n```C\nvoid calculateMaxFruitsForCompote(int a, int b, int c, int *out)\n{\n    *out = (a >= 1 && b >= 2 * a && c >= 4 * a) ?                     "tokens_used": 0,
                    "code": "/*\n    Nikolay has a lemons, b apples and c pears. He decided to cook a compote. According to the recipe the fruits should be in the ratio 1: 2: 4 . It means that for each lemon in the compote should be exactly 2 apples and exactly 4 pears. You can't crumble up, break up or cut these fruits into pieces. These fruits \u2014 lemons, apples and pears \u2014 should be put in the compote as whole fruits. Your task is to determine the maximum total number of lemons, apples and pears from which Nikolay can cook the compote. It is possible that Nikolay can't use any fruits, in this case print 0 .\n\n    Input\n    The input contains the positive integer a (1 \u2264 a \u2264 1000) \u2014 the number of lemons Nikolay has. The second line contains the positive integer b (1 \u2264 b \u2264 1000) \u2014 the number of apples Nikolay has. The third line contains the positive integer c (1 \u2264 c \u2264 1000) \u2014 the number of pears Nikolay has.\n\n    Output\n    Output the maximum total number of lemons, apples and pears from which Nikolay can cook the compote.\n*/\n/*@ predicate isValidSolution(integer a, integer b, integer c, integer out) =\n    \\exists integer a_used, b_used, c_used;\n    0 <= a_used <= a &&\n    0 <= b_used <= b &&\n    0 <= c_used <= c &&\n    4 * a_used == 2 * b_used == c_used &&\n    a_used + b_used + c_used == out;\n*/\n\n/*@ predicate existsLargerSolution(integer a, integer b, integer c, integer out) =\n    \\exists integer a_used, b_used, c_used;\n    0 <= a_used <= a &&\n    0 <= b_used <= b &&\n    0 <= c_used <= c &&\n    4 * a_used == 2 * b_used == c_used &&\n    a_used + b_used + c_used > out;\n*/\n\n/*@\n    requires \\valid(out);\n    requires 1 <= a <= 1000;\n    requires 1 <= b <= 1000;\n    requires 1 <= c <= 1000;\n    assigns *out;\n    ensures isValidSolution(a, b, c, *out);\n    ensures !existsLargerSolution(a, b, c, *out);\n*/\nvoid calculateMaxFruitsForCompote(int a, int b, int c, int *out) {\n    int applesNeeded = 2 * a;\n    int pearsNeeded = 4 * a;\n    \n    int totalFruits = (b >= applesNeeded && c >= pearsNeeded) ? Additionally it checks if a given integer x is a multiple of another integer div.  If either condition is not satisfied, the function returns false. This operation ensures that x adheres to specific numeric constraints related to both value and divisibility.\n\n    input:\n        The function takes four integers x, low, high and div. x is the number to be checked, and low and high are the lower and upper bounds of the range, respectively. According to the recipe the fruits should be in the ratio 1: 2: 4 . It means that for each lemon in the compote should be exactly 2 apples and exactly 4 pears. You can't crumble up, break up or cut these fruits into pieces. These fruits \u2014 lemons, apples and pears \u2014 should be put in the compote as whole fruits. Your task is to determine the maximum total number of lemons, apples and pears from which Nikolay can cook the compote. It is possible that Nikolay can't use any fruits, in this case print 0 .\n\n    Input\n    The input contains the positive integer a (1 \u2264 a \u2264 1000) \u2014 the number of lemons Nikolay has. The second line contains the positive integer b (1 \u2264 b \u2264 1000) \u2014 the number of apples Nikolay has. The third line contains the positive integer c (1 \u2264 c \u2264 1000) \u2014 the number of pears Nikolay has.\n\n    Output\n    Output the maximum total number of lemons, apples and pears from which Nikolay can cook the compote.\n*/\n\nvoid calculateMaxFruitsForCompote(int a, int b, int c, int *out);\n```\nThe previous code attempt did not verify: \n```C\nvoid calculateMaxFruitsForCompote(int a, int b, int c, int *out)\n{\n    *out = (a >= 1 && b >= 2 * a && c >= 4 * a) ?                     "code": "/*\n    Nikolay has a lemons, b apples and c pears. He decided to cook a compote. According to the recipe the fruits should be in the ratio 1: 2: 4 . It means that for each lemon in the compote should be exactly 2 apples and exactly 4 pears. You can't crumble up, break up or cut these fruits into pieces. These fruits \u2014 lemons, apples and pears \u2014 should be put in the compote as whole fruits. Your task is to determine the maximum total number of lemons, apples and pears from which Nikolay can cook the compote. It is possible that Nikolay can't use any fruits, in this case print 0 .\n\n    Input\n    The input contains the positive integer a (1 \u2264 a \u2264 1000) \u2014 the number of lemons Nikolay has. The second line contains the positive integer b (1 \u2264 b \u2264 1000) \u2014 the number of apples Nikolay has. The third line contains the positive integer c (1 \u2264 c \u2264 1000) \u2014 the number of pears Nikolay has.\n\n    Output\n    Output the maximum total number of lemons, apples and pears from which Nikolay can cook the compote.\n*/\n/*@ predicate isValidSolution(integer a, integer b, integer c, integer out) =\n    \\exists integer a_used, b_used, c_used;\n    0 <= a_used <= a &&\n    0 <= b_used <= b &&\n    0 <= c_used <= c &&\n    4 * a_used == 2 * b_used == c_used &&\n    a_used + b_used + c_used == out;\n*/\n\n/*@ predicate existsLargerSolution(integer a, integer b, integer c, integer out) =\n    \\exists integer a_used, b_used, c_used;\n    0 <= a_used <= a &&\n    0 <= b_used <= b &&\n    0 <= c_used <= c &&\n    4 * a_used == 2 * b_used == c_used &&\n    a_used + b_used + c_used > out;\n*/\n\n/*@\n    requires \\valid(out);\n    requires 1 <= a <= 1000;\n    requires 1 <= b <= 1000;\n    requires 1 <= c <= 1000;\n    assigns *out;\n    ensures isValidSolution(a, b, c, *out);\n    ensures !existsLargerSolution(a, b, c, *out);\n*/\nvoid calculateMaxFruitsForCompote(int a, int b, int c, int *out) {\n    int applesNeeded = 2 * a;\n    int pearsNeeded = 4 * a;\n\n    int totalFruits = 0;\n  \n    if (b >= applesNeeded && c >= pearsNeeded) {\n        totalFruits = a + b + c;\n    }\n\n    *out = totalFruits;\n}\n",

This operation ensures that x adheres to specific numeric constraints related to both value and divisibility.\n\n    input:\n        The function takes four integers x, low, high and div. x is the number to be checked, and low and high are the lower and upper bounds of the range, respectively. The function also takes an integer div which is the number to be checked for divisibility.\n\n    output:\n        One output will be given which returns true if both conditions are met, i.e., if x is within the range [low, high] and simultaneously a multiple of div.\n*/\nvoid checkConstraints(int x, int low, int high, int div, int *out)\n{\n    *out = (x >= low && x <= high && x % div == 0);\n}\n```\n\nYou must adhere to the following rules:\n * Do not add an explanation to the code\n * Only give the output function, do not repeat the specification\n * Do not make use of any type of loops. According to the recipe the fruits should be in the ratio 1: 2: 4 . It means that for each lemon in the compote should be exactly 2 apples and exactly 4 pears. You can't crumble up, break up or cut these fruits into pieces. These fruits \u2014 lemons, apples and pears \u2014 should be put in the compote as whole fruits. Your task is to determine the maximum total number of lemons, apples and pears from which Nikolay can cook the compote. It is possible that Nikolay can't use any fruits, in this case print 0 .\n\n    Input\n    The input contains the positive integer a (1 \u2264 a \u2264 1000) \u2014 the number of lemons Nikolay has. The second line contains the positive integer b (1 \u2264 b \u2264 1000) \u2014 the number of apples Nikolay has. The third line contains the positive integer c (1 \u2264 c \u2264 1000) \u2014 the number of pears Nikolay has.\n\n    Output\n    Output the maximum total number of lemons, apples and pears from which Nikolay can cook the compote.\n*/\n\nvoid calculateMaxFruitsForCompote(int a, int b, int c, int *out);\n```\nThe previous code attempt did not verify: \n```C\nvoid calculateMaxFruitsForCompote(int a, int b, int c, int *out)\n{\n    int totalLemonsNeeded = 1;\n    int totalApplesNeeded = 2 * totalLemonsNeeded;\n    int totalPearsNeeded = 4 * totalLemonsNeeded;\n\n    int totalFruits = totalLemonsNeeded + totalApplesNeeded + totalPearsNeeded;\n\n    *out = (a >= totalLemonsNeeded && b >= totalApplesNeeded && c >= totalPearsNeeded) ? (totalFruits) : 0;\n}\n```Improve the code such that it formally verifies.\nPlease generate the formally verified C code adhering to the problem description.",

It means that for each lemon in the compote should be exactly 2 apples and exactly 4 pears. You can't crumble up, break up or cut these fruits into pieces. These fruits \u2014 lemons, apples and pears \u2014 should be put in the compote as whole fruits. Your task is to determine the maximum total number of lemons, apples and pears from which Nikolay can cook the compote. It is possible that Nikolay can't use any fruits, in this case print 0 .\n\n    Input\n    The input contains the positive integer a (1 \u2264 a \u2264 1000) \u2014 the number of lemons Nikolay has. The second line contains the positive integer b (1 \u2264 b \u2264 1000) \u2014 the number of apples Nikolay has. The third line contains the positive integer c (1 \u2264 c \u2264 1000) \u2014 the number of pears Nikolay has.\n\n    Output\n    Output the maximum total number of lemons, apples and pears from which Nikolay can cook the compote.\n*/\n/*@ predicate isValidSolution(integer a, integer b, integer c, integer out) =\n    \\exists integer a_used, b_used, c_used;\n    0 <= a_used <= a &&\n    0 <= b_used <= b &&\n    0 <= c_used <= c &&\n    4 * a_used == 2 * b_used == c_used &&\n    a_used + b_used + c_used == out;\n*/\n\n/*@ predicate existsLargerSolution(integer a, integer b, integer c, integer out) =\n    \\exists integer a_used, b_used, c_used;\n    0 <= a_used <= a &&\n    0 <= b_used <= b &&\n    0 <= c_used <= c &&\n    4 * a_used == 2 * b_used == c_used &&\n    a_used + b_used + c_used > out;\n*/\n\n/*@\n    requires \\valid(out);\n    requires 1 <= a <= 1000;\n    requires 1 <= b <= 1000;\n    requires 1 <= c <= 1000;\n    assigns *out;\n    ensures isValidSolution(a, b, c, *out);\n    ensures !existsLargerSolution(a, b, c, *out);\n*/\nvoid calculateMaxFruitsForCompote(int a, int b, int c, int *out) {\n    int totalLemonsNeeded = 1;\n    int totalApplesNeeded = 2;\n    int totalPearsNeeded = 4;\n\n    int totalFruits = totalLemonsNeeded + totalApplesNeeded + totalPearsNeeded;\n    int maxLemons = a / totalLemonsNeeded;\n    int maxApples = b / totalApplesNeeded;\n    int maxPears = c / totalPearsNeeded;\n\n    *out = (maxLemons > 0 && maxApples > 0 && maxPears > 0) ? You must write a function that adheres to this problem specification, such that the code will be formally verified using Frama-C.\n\nHere is an example of the task:\n```C\n/*\n    Check if a given number falls within a specified range between two integers low and high, inclusive. Additionally it checks if a given integer x is a multiple of another integer div.  If either condition is not satisfied, the function returns false. This operation ensures that x adheres to specific numeric constraints related to both value and divisibility.\n\n    input:\n        The function takes four integers x, low, high and div. x is the number to be checked, and low and high are the lower and upper bounds of the range, respectively. The function also takes an integer div which is the number to be checked for divisibility.\n\n    output:\n        One output will be given which returns true if both conditions are met, i.e., if x is within the range [low, high] and simultaneously a multiple of div.\n*/\nvoid checkConstraints(int x, int low, int high, int div, int *out)\n{\n    *out = (x >= low && x <= high && x % div == 0);\n}\n```\n\nYou must adhere to the following rules:\n * Do not add an explanation to the code\n * Only give the output function, do not repeat the specification\n * Do not make use of any type of loops. That is, no for, while, do-while or recursive loops\n\nYou are given the following problem description. You must return the code in the following format:\n```C\n/*\n    Nikolay has a lemons, b apples and c pears. He decided to cook a compote. According to the recipe the fruits should be in the ratio 1: 2: 4 . It means that for each lemon in the compote should be exactly 2 apples and exactly 4 pears. You can't crumble up, break up or cut these fruits into pieces. These fruits \u2014 lemons, apples and pears \u2014 should be put in the compote as whole fruits. Your task is to determine the maximum total number of lemons, apples and pears from which Nikolay can cook the compote. The third line contains the positive integer c (1 \u2264 c \u2264 1000) \u2014 the number of pears Nikolay has.\n\n    Output\n    Output the maximum total number of lemons, apples and pears from which Nikolay can cook the compote.\n*/\n/*@ predicate isValidSolution(integer a, integer b, integer c, integer out) =\n    \\exists integer a_used, b_used, c_used;\n    0 <= a_used <= a &&\n    0 <= b_used <= b &&\n    0 <= c_used <= c &&\n    4 * a_used == 2 * b_used == c_used &&\n    a_used + b_used + c_used == out;\n*/\n\n/*@ predicate existsLargerSolution(integer a, integer b, integer c, integer out) =\n    \\exists integer a_used, b_used, c_used;\n    0 <= a_used <= a &&\n    0 <= b_used <= b &&\n    0 <= c_used <= c &&\n    4 * a_used == 2 * b_used == c_used &&\n    a_used + b_used + c_used > out;\n*/\n\n/*@\n    requires \\valid(out);\n    requires 1 <= a <= 1000;\n    requires 1 <= b <= 1000;\n    requires 1 <= c <= 1000;\n    assigns *out;\n    ensures isValidSolution(a, b, c, *out);\n    ensures !existsLargerSolution(a, b, c, *out);\n*/\nvoid calculateMaxFruitsForCompote(int a, int b, int c, int *out) {\n    int totalLemonsNeeded = 1;\n    int totalApplesNeeded = 2 * totalLemonsNeeded;\n    int totalPearsNeeded = 4 * totalLemonsNeeded;\n\n    int totalFruits = totalLemonsNeeded + totalApplesNeeded + totalPearsNeeded;\n\n    int validLemons = (a >= totalLemonsNeeded);\n    int validApples = (b >= totalApplesNeeded);\n    int validPears = (c >= totalPearsNeeded);\n\n    int validTotalFruits = validLemons && validApples && validPears;\n    *out = validTotalFruits ? totalFruits : 0;\n}\n",

Additionally it checks if a given integer x is a multiple of another integer div.  If either condition is not satisfied, the function returns false. This operation ensures that x adheres to specific numeric constraints related to both value and divisibility.\n\n    input:\n        The function takes four integers x, low, high and div. x is the number to be checked, and low and high are the lower and upper bounds of the range, respectively. The function also takes an integer div which is the number to be checked for divisibility.\n\n    output:\n        One output will be given which returns true if both conditions are met, i.e., if x is within the range [low, high] and simultaneously a multiple of div.\n*/\nvoid checkConstraints(int x, int low, int high, int div, int *out)\n{\n    *out = (x >= low && x <= high && x % div == 0);\n}\n```\n\nYou must adhere to the following rules:\n * Do not add an explanation to the code\n * Only give the output function, do not repeat the specification\n * Do not make use of any type of loops. That is, no for, while, do-while or recursive loops\n\nYou are given the following problem description. You must return the code in the following format:\n```C\n/*\n    Nikolay has a lemons, b apples and c pears. He decided to cook a compote. According to the recipe the fruits should be in the ratio 1: 2: 4 . It means that for each lemon in the compote should be exactly 2 apples and exactly 4 pears. You can't crumble up, break up or cut these fruits into pieces. These fruits \u2014 lemons, apples and pears \u2014 should be put in the compote as whole fruits. Your task is to determine the maximum total number of lemons, apples and pears from which Nikolay can cook the compote. Additionally it checks if a given integer x is a multiple of another integer div.  If either condition is not satisfied, the function returns false. This operation ensures that x adheres to specific numeric constraints related to both value and divisibility.\n\n    input:\n        The function takes four integers x, low, high and div. x is the number to be checked, and low and high are the lower and upper bounds of the range, respectively. The function also takes an integer div which is the number to be checked for divisibility.\n\n    output:\n        One output will be given which returns true if both conditions are met, i.e., if x is within the range [low, high] and simultaneously a multiple of div.\n*/\nvoid checkConstraints(int x, int low, int high, int div, int *out)\n{\n    *out = (x >= low && x <= high && x % div == 0);\n}\n```\n\nYou must adhere to the following rules:\n * Do not add an explanation to the code\n * Only give the output function, do not repeat the specification\n * Do not make use of any type of loops. That is, no for, while, do-while or recursive loops\n\nYou are given the following problem description. You must return the code in the following format:\n```C\n/*\n    Nikolay has a lemons, b apples and c pears. He decided to cook a compote. According to the recipe the fruits should be in the ratio 1: 2: 4 . It means that for each lemon in the compote should be exactly 2 apples and exactly 4 pears. You can't crumble up, break up or cut these fruits into pieces. These fruits \u2014 lemons, apples and pears \u2014 should be put in the compote as whole fruits. Your task is to determine the maximum total number of lemons, apples and pears from which Nikolay can cook the compote. You can't crumble up, break up or cut these fruits into pieces. These fruits \u2014 lemons, apples and pears \u2014 should be put in the compote as whole fruits. Your task is to determine the maximum total number of lemons, apples and pears from which Nikolay can cook the compote. These fruits \u2014 lemons, apples and pears \u2014 should be put in the compote as whole fruits. Your task is to determine the maximum total number of lemons, apples and pears from which Nikolay can cook the compote. It is possible that Nikolay can't use any fruits, in this case print 0 .\n\n    Input\n    The input contains the positive integer a (1 \u2264 a \u2264 1000) \u2014 the number of lemons Nikolay has. The second line contains the positive integer b (1 \u2264 b \u2264 1000) \u2014 the number of apples Nikolay has. The third line contains the positive integer c (1 \u2264 c \u2264 1000) \u2014 the number of pears Nikolay has.\n\n    Output\n    Output the maximum total number of lemons, apples and pears from which Nikolay can cook the compote.\n*/\n/*@ predicate isValidSolution(integer a, integer b, integer c, integer out) =\n    \\exists integer a_used, b_used, c_used;\n    0 <= a_used <= a &&\n    0 <= b_used <= b &&\n    0 <= c_used <= c &&\n    4 * a_used == 2 * b_used == c_used &&\n    a_used + b_used + c_used == out;\n*/\n\n/*@ predicate existsLargerSolution(integer a, integer b, integer c, integer out) =\n    \\exists integer a_used, b_used, c_used;\n    0 <= a_used <= a &&\n    0 <= b_used <= b &&\n    0 <= c_used <= c &&\n    4 * a_used == 2 * b_used == c_used &&\n    a_used + b_used + c_used > out;\n*/\n\n/*@\n    requires \\valid(out);\n    requires 1 <= a <= 1000;\n    requires 1 <= b <= 1000;\n    requires 1 <= c <= 1000;\n    assigns *out;\n    ensures isValidSolution(a, b, c, *out);\n    ensures !existsLargerSolution(a, b, c, *out);\n*/\nvoid calculateMaxFruitsForCompote(int a, int b, int c, int *out) {\n    int totalLemonsNeeded = 1;\n    int totalApplesNeeded = 2;\n    int totalPearsNeeded = 4;\n\n    int totalFruits = totalLemonsNeeded + totalApplesNeeded + totalPearsNeeded;\n\n    int validLemons = (a >= totalLemonsNeeded);\n    int validApples = (b >= totalApplesNeeded);\n    int validPears = (c >= totalPearsNeeded);\n\n    *out = (validLemons && validApples && validPears) ? (totalFruits) : 0;\n}\n",

The third line contains the positive integer c (1 \u2264 c \u2264 1000) \u2014 the number of pears Nikolay has.\n\n    Output\n    Output the maximum total number of lemons, apples and pears from which Nikolay can cook the compote.\n*/\n/*@ predicate isValidSolution(integer a, integer b, integer c, integer out) =\n    \\exists integer a_used, b_used, c_used;\n    0 <= a_used <= a &&\n    0 <= b_used <= b &&\n    0 <= c_used <= c &&\n    4 * a_used == 2 * b_used == c_used &&\n    a_used + b_used + c_used == out;\n*/\n\n/*@ predicate existsLargerSolution(integer a, integer b, integer c, integer out) =\n    \\exists integer a_used, b_used, c_used;\n    0 <= a_used <= a &&\n    0 <= b_used <= b &&\n    0 <= c_used <= c &&\n    4 * a_used == 2 * b_used == c_used &&\n    a_used + b_used + c_used > out;\n*/\n\n/*@\n    requires \\valid(out);\n    requires 1 <= a <= 1000;\n    requires 1 <= b <= 1000;\n    requires 1 <= c <= 1000;\n    assigns *out;\n    ensures isValidSolution(a, b, c, *out);\n    ensures !existsLargerSolution(a, b, c, *out);\n*/\nvoid calculateMaxFruitsForCompote(int a, int b, int c, int *out) {\n    int minRatio = 1 + 2 + 4;\n    \n    if (a >= 1 && b >= 2 && c >= 4)\n    {\n        int numSetsA = a / 1;\n        int numSetsB = b / 2;\n        int numSetsC = c / 4;\n        \n        int maxSets = numSetsA < numSetsB ? numSetsA : numSetsB;\n        maxSets = maxSets < numSetsC ? maxSets : numSetsC;\n        \n        *out = maxSets * minRatio;\n    }\n    else\n    {\n        *out = 0;\n    }\n}\n",
